var tafsirData_22 = {
  1: {
    "O humanity! Fear your Lord": "This is a universal call to all of mankind—not just believers, but every human being who has ever lived or will ever live. Allah is commanding everyone to be conscious of Him, to be mindful of His presence, His power, and His ability to hold us accountable. Fearing Allah means obeying His commands, avoiding what He has forbidden, and preparing for the meeting with Him. This address reminds us that regardless of our background, race, or status, we all share one Lord and Creator who deserves our reverence.",
    "for the ˹violent˺ quaking at the Hour is surely a dreadful thing": "The 'Hour' refers to the Day of Resurrection, when this world will come to an end and all people will be raised to stand before Allah for judgment. The 'quaking' describes the violent shaking and trembling that will occur when this Day arrives. The earth itself will convulse in a way never experienced before. Allah describes this event as 'a dreadful thing'—something so severe and terrifying that nothing in this world can compare to it. This is meant to awaken us from heedlessness and make us take our preparation for that Day seriously."
  },
  2: {
    "The Day you see it, every nursing mother will abandon what she is nursing": "To understand the magnitude of this terror, consider that a nursing mother has one of the strongest bonds in creation with her infant. She would normally never abandon her baby under any circumstance. Yet on that Day, the horror will be so overwhelming that even this most caring of mothers will forget her nursing child and be completely absorbed in her own fear. This is not because she becomes heartless, but because the terror of that moment will be beyond anything the human mind can process.",
    "and every pregnant woman will deliver her burden ˹prematurely˺": "The shock and fear of that Day will be so intense that pregnant women will miscarry from sheer terror. This vivid image shows us that the normal functions of the body will be completely disrupted by the overwhelming nature of what people will witness. These descriptions are meant to help us grasp, even slightly, what awaits on that Day.",
    "And you will see people ˹as if they were˺ drunk, though they will not be drunk": "People will appear disoriented, confused, and staggering as if they had consumed alcohol. They will be unable to walk straight, unable to think clearly, unable to focus. But Allah clarifies that this is not from any intoxicant—their minds will be fully aware, which makes it even more terrifying. They will be completely conscious of the horror unfolding before them.",
    "but the torment of Allah is ˹terribly˺ severe": "The reason for this state of confusion and terror is the severity of Allah's punishment and the overwhelming nature of that Day. This conclusion reminds us that Allah's power is absolute, and His punishment for those who rejected His guidance is something we should all fear and work to avoid through sincere faith and good deeds."
  },
  3: {
    "˹Still˺ there are some who dispute about Allah without knowledge": "Despite the clear warnings about the Day of Judgment, there are people who argue about Allah—His existence, His attributes, His power to resurrect, or His right to be worshipped alone—without any sound knowledge or evidence. They speak about matters of the unseen and divine realities based on ignorance, personal opinion, or blind following of others. This verse highlights how dangerous it is to speak about Allah without proper knowledge, as it leads to misguidance.",
    "and follow every rebellious devil": "These people, instead of following divine guidance, choose to follow devils—whether from among the jinn or misguiding humans who rebel against Allah. The word 'rebellious' indicates that these devils are persistent in their disobedience and determined to lead others astray. When someone rejects the truth, they become vulnerable to following any corrupting influence that appeals to their desires."
  },
  4: {
    "It has been decreed for such devils that whoever takes them as a guide will be misguided": "Allah has decreed and written in the fate of these rebellious devils that their role is to misguide. Anyone who chooses to follow them, trust them, or take them as allies will inevitably be led astray from the straight path. This is a warning that the choice of who we follow and listen to has eternal consequences.",
    "and led by them into the torment of the Blaze": "The ultimate destination of following such devils is the Hellfire. Those who allow themselves to be guided by rebellion against Allah will find that their guides have led them straight into eternal punishment. This verse serves as a stark warning about the company we keep and the influences we allow into our lives."
  },
  5: {
    "O humanity! If you are in doubt about the Resurrection": "Allah addresses those who question whether people can truly be brought back to life after death. This doubt existed among the disbelievers of Makkah and continues today among skeptics. Allah responds to this doubt with undeniable evidence from our own existence.",
    "then ˹know that˺ We did create you from dust": "The first human, Adam (peace be upon him), was created from dust of the earth. This is the origin of all humanity. If Allah could create a living, thinking human being from mere dirt, surely He can recreate us after we return to dust.",
    "then from a sperm-drop": "After Adam, every human being originates from a tiny drop of fluid—something so small and seemingly insignificant, yet it contains all the potential for a complete human being. This transformation from something so simple to something so complex is a miracle we often overlook.",
    "then ˹developed you into˺ a clinging clot ˹of blood˺": "The sperm-drop develops into a clot that attaches itself to the wall of the womb. This stage, confirmed by modern embryology, shows the precise stages of development that Allah has ordained.",
    "then a lump of flesh—fully formed or unformed": "The embryo then becomes a small piece of flesh. Some embryos are 'fully formed'—meaning they will continue to develop into complete human beings, while others are 'unformed'—pregnancies that do not continue. Allah decides which will proceed and which will not.",
    "in order to demonstrate ˹Our power˺ to you": "All these stages of development are signs and proofs of Allah's creative power. He is showing us through our own creation that He is capable of anything, including bringing us back to life.",
    "˹Then˺ We settle whatever ˹embryo˺ We will in the womb for an appointed term": "Allah determines which pregnancies will continue to full term. Each pregnancy has a decreed duration, and Allah alone decides its outcome. This shows His complete control over life from its earliest stages.",
    "then bring you forth as infants": "After the appointed time in the womb, Allah brings us out as helpless babies, completely dependent on others for survival.",
    "so that you may reach your prime": "Allah then allows us to grow, develop strength, intelligence, and capabilities until we reach the peak of our physical and mental abilities—our prime years.",
    "Some of you ˹may˺ die ˹young˺": "Not everyone reaches old age. Some people die in childhood, youth, or middle age. The timing of death is in Allah's hands alone.",
    "while others are left to reach the most feeble stage of life so that they may know nothing after having known much": "Some people live to such an advanced age that they lose their memory and mental faculties, returning to a state of dependence like infancy. A person who was once a scholar or expert may forget everything they knew. This cycle of life demonstrates Allah's power and reminds us that our abilities are gifts that can be taken away.",
    "And you see the earth lifeless": "Allah now gives another example—look at the earth during drought or winter. It appears completely dead, with no vegetation, no growth, no sign of life.",
    "but as soon as We send down rain upon it, it begins to stir ˹to life˺ and swell, producing every type of pleasant plant": "When rain falls on this dead earth, it suddenly comes alive—swelling with moisture, sprouting plants, producing beautiful vegetation of all kinds. Just as Allah brings the dead earth back to life, He will bring the dead back to life on the Day of Resurrection. This is an observable proof that we witness every year."
  },
  6: {
    "That is because Allah ˹alone˺ is the Truth": "All these signs and proofs demonstrate that Allah is the ultimate Truth and Reality. Everything else is temporary and dependent on Him, but He is eternal, self-sufficient, and the source of all existence.",
    "He ˹alone˺ gives life to the dead": "Only Allah has the power to bring the dead back to life—whether it is the dead earth through rain or dead human beings on the Day of Resurrection. No one else shares this ability.",
    "and He ˹alone˺ is Most Capable of everything": "There is nothing beyond Allah's power. The One who created you the first time, who develops you through all these stages, and who revives the dead earth, is certainly able to resurrect you for judgment."
  },
  7: {
    "And certainly the Hour is coming, there is no doubt about it": "After presenting all this evidence of Allah's creative power, He affirms with certainty that the Day of Judgment will definitely come. There is no room for doubt or speculation—it is an absolute certainty, as certain as the sun rising each day.",
    "And Allah will surely resurrect those in the graves": "Every person who has ever died and been buried—or whose body has decomposed in any way—will be brought back to life by Allah. No matter how long ago they died, no matter what happened to their remains, Allah will gather them all for the final reckoning."
  },
  8: {
    "˹Still˺ there are some who dispute about Allah without knowledge": "Despite all the clear evidence presented, some people persist in arguing about Allah. They have no real knowledge—no sound understanding based on evidence or reason.",
    "guidance": "They also lack guidance—meaning they have not followed any prophet, accepted any divine message, or opened their hearts to truth.",
    "or an enlightening scripture": "And they have no scripture or revealed book to support their claims. They argue based on nothing but their own arrogance, desires, and baseless opinions. This verse describes people who reject truth despite having no legitimate basis for their rejection."
  },
  9: {
    "turning away ˹in pride˺ to lead ˹others˺ astray from Allah's Way": "These arrogant disputers not only reject the truth themselves but actively work to mislead others. They turn their necks away in pride when the truth is presented to them, and they use their influence to prevent others from following Allah's path. This is a double crime—rejecting guidance and blocking others from it.",
    "They will suffer disgrace in this world": "Such people will face humiliation and disgrace even in this life. This may come in the form of defeat, exposure of their falsehood, loss of reputation, or other forms of worldly punishment.",
    "and on the Day of Judgment We will make them taste the torment of burning": "But the greater punishment awaits them in the Hereafter, where they will experience the burning torment of Hellfire—a just consequence for their arrogance and their efforts to mislead others."
  },
  10: {
    "˹They will be told,˺ \"This is ˹the reward˺ for what your hands have done": "On that Day, they will be told that their punishment is a direct result of their own choices and actions. They earned this fate through their own deeds—their arrogance, their rejection of truth, and their efforts to misguide others. No one else is to blame.",
    "And Allah is never unjust to ˹His˺ creation": "Allah emphasizes that He is perfectly just. He does not wrong anyone even by the smallest amount. Every person receives exactly what they deserve based on their choices. The punishment of the wicked is not oppression—it is justice."
  },
  11: {
    "And there are some who worship Allah on the verge ˹of faith˺": "This describes people whose faith is not deeply rooted. They stand at the edge of Islam—not fully committed, not truly convinced. Their connection to the religion is superficial and conditional. They are like someone standing at the edge of a cliff—any disturbance can cause them to fall.",
    "if they are blessed with something good, they are content with it": "When life goes well for them—when they have health, wealth, success, and comfort—they are happy with their faith. They see Islam as beneficial because their circumstances are favorable. Their worship is based on worldly results, not sincere belief.",
    "but if they are afflicted with a trial, they relapse ˹into disbelief˺": "However, when difficulty comes—illness, poverty, loss, or any hardship—they abandon their faith entirely. They turn their backs on Islam, blaming the religion or even Allah for their troubles. This shows their faith was never genuine; it was merely a transaction based on worldly benefits.",
    "losing this world and the Hereafter": "Such a person loses everything. By abandoning faith during trials, they lose the peace and resilience that true faith provides in this world. And by dying in disbelief, they lose the eternal rewards of the Hereafter. They gain nothing and lose everything.",
    "That is ˹truly˺ the clearest loss": "Allah describes this as the most obvious and complete form of loss. There is no loss greater than losing both worlds—the temporary comfort of this life and the eternal bliss of the next."
  },
  12: {
    "They call besides Allah what can neither harm nor benefit them": "When these weak-faithed people abandon Allah, they turn to false gods, idols, or other objects of worship that have absolutely no power. These false deities cannot help them in any way, nor can they harm them if they stop worshipping them. They are completely powerless.",
    "That is ˹truly˺ the farthest one can stray": "Turning away from the All-Powerful Allah to worship powerless entities represents the ultimate deviation from truth. It is the furthest point of misguidance—to leave the One who can actually help and turn to that which cannot."
  },
  13: {
    "They invoke those whose worship leads to harm, not benefit": "Not only are these false gods unable to help, but worshipping them actually brings harm. The harm of associating partners with Allah (shirk) is far greater than any imagined benefit. Such worship leads to punishment in this life and the next.",
    "What an evil patron and what an evil associate!": "Allah condemns these false objects of worship in the strongest terms. They are terrible protectors—offering no real protection. They are terrible companions—leading only to ruin. This is a powerful condemnation of anything worshipped besides Allah."
  },
  14: {
    "Indeed, Allah will admit those who believe and do good into Gardens, under which rivers flow": "In contrast to those with weak faith, Allah promises that true believers—those who have sincere faith combined with righteous actions—will be admitted into Paradise. This Paradise is described as gardens with rivers flowing beneath them, a place of eternal beauty, comfort, and joy. Faith alone is not enough; it must be accompanied by good deeds.",
    "Surely Allah does what He wills": "Allah's will is absolute. When He decides to reward His faithful servants, nothing can prevent Him. And when He decides to punish the arrogant disbelievers, nothing can stop Him. This statement reinforces both His promise and His warning."
  },
  15: {
    "Whoever thinks that Allah will not help His Prophet in this world and the Hereafter": "Some enemies of the Prophet (peace be upon him) were enraged by the spread of Islam and frustrated that Allah continued to support His Messenger. They wished for the Prophet's defeat and the failure of his mission. This verse addresses such people.",
    "let them stretch out a rope to the ceiling and strangle themselves": "Allah challenges these angry opponents: if your rage at Allah's support for His Prophet is so unbearable, go ahead and hang yourself in frustration. This is a rhetorical challenge showing the futility of opposing Allah's decree.",
    "then let them see if this plan will do away with ˹the cause of˺ their rage": "Even if they took such extreme measures, it would not change anything. Allah's support for His Prophet and His religion will continue regardless of their opposition. Their rage and plots are useless against Allah's divine plan. This verse powerfully demonstrates that nothing can thwart Allah's will."
  },
  16: {
    "And so We revealed this ˹Quran˺ as clear verses": "Allah sent down the Quran with clear, evident verses that leave no room for confusion. The guidance is plain, the truth is manifest, and the message is unmistakable for anyone who sincerely seeks it.",
    "And Allah certainly guides whoever He wills": "While the Quran's verses are clear, ultimate guidance comes from Allah. He guides those who sincerely seek truth and turn to Him with humble hearts. This does not mean guidance is arbitrary—rather, Allah guides those who make the effort and opens the doors for those who knock."
  },
  17: {
    "Indeed, the believers, Jews, Sabians, Christians, Magi, and the polytheists": "Allah mentions all the major religious groups that existed at the time of revelation and that continue to exist. The believers (Muslims), the Jews, the Sabians (an ancient religious group), the Christians, the Magi (Zoroastrians), and the polytheists (those who worship multiple gods or idols)—all these different groups with their conflicting claims and beliefs.",
    "Allah will judge between them ˹all˺ on Judgment Day": "Rather than these groups fighting endlessly over who is right, Allah will settle all disputes on the Day of Judgment. He will make clear who was upon truth and who was upon falsehood. No one will be able to argue or deny the verdict.",
    "Surely Allah is a Witness over all things": "Allah sees and knows everything—every belief held, every action done, every secret intention. Nothing escapes His knowledge, and He will judge with perfect justice based on complete knowledge of all that occurred."
  },
  18: {
    "Do you not see that to Allah bow down ˹in submission˺ all those in the heavens and all those on the earth": "Everything in creation submits to Allah's authority. The angels in the heavens and all creatures on earth acknowledge His lordship and follow His commands, whether willingly or by the nature of their existence.",
    "as well as the sun, the moon, the stars, the mountains, the trees, and ˹all˺ living beings": "Even the celestial bodies—the sun, moon, and stars—prostrate to Allah by following the orbits and laws He set for them. The mountains stand firm, the trees grow, and all living creatures exist according to His will. All of creation glorifies Allah in ways we may not perceive.",
    "as well as many humans": "Among humanity, many people willingly submit to Allah, recognizing His right to be worshipped and obeying His commands. These are the believers who prostrate to Allah by choice.",
    "while many are deserving of punishment": "However, many humans refuse to submit willingly, despite being subject to Allah's control just like everything else. These arrogant ones deserve punishment for their rejection.",
    "And whoever Allah disgraces, none can honour": "If Allah decrees humiliation for someone due to their arrogance and disbelief, no one can restore their honor. No power on earth can elevate someone whom Allah has debased.",
    "Surely Allah does what He wills": "Allah's will is supreme and unchallenged. He honors whom He wills and humiliates whom He wills, based on His perfect wisdom and justice."
  },
  19: {
    "These are two opposing groups that disagree about their Lord": "Allah describes believers and disbelievers as two opposing parties who have fundamentally different positions regarding their Lord. The believers affirm His oneness, worship Him alone, and follow His guidance. The disbelievers reject, deny, and oppose. This opposition will be settled on the Day of Judgment.",
    "as for the disbelievers, garments of Fire will be cut out for them": "In a terrifying image, Allah describes how garments made of fire will be tailored specifically for the disbelievers. Just as clothes are cut to fit a person, these garments of fire will be made to cover and burn them completely.",
    "and boiling water will be poured over their heads": "In addition to being clothed in fire, scalding hot water will be poured over their heads, adding to their torment from above."
  },
  20: {
    "melting whatever is in their bellies, along with their skin": "This boiling water is so intensely hot that it will melt their internal organs and their skin. The punishment reaches both the inside and outside of their bodies. This description is meant to convey the unbearable severity of the punishment awaiting those who rejected Allah."
  },
  21: {
    "And awaiting them are maces of iron": "In addition to fire and boiling water, the inhabitants of Hell will be beaten with heavy iron clubs or maces. These are instruments of punishment wielded by the angels of Hell to inflict further suffering on those who rejected their Lord."
  },
  22: {
    "Whenever they try to escape from Hell—out of anguish—they will be forced back into it": "The disbelievers will desperately try to escape the unbearable torment of Hell. Driven by extreme anguish and desperation, they will attempt to flee, but they will be pushed back into the fire. There is no escape from Allah's punishment.",
    "˹and will be told,˺ \"Taste the torment of burning!\"": "As they are forced back into the flames, they will be told to taste the burning punishment—a reminder that this is the consequence of their choices in the worldly life. The word 'taste' emphasizes that they will fully experience every aspect of this torment."
  },
  23: {
    "˹But˺ Allah will surely admit those who believe and do good into Gardens, under which rivers flow": "In beautiful contrast to the horrific punishment of disbelievers, Allah describes the reward awaiting the faithful. Those who combined sincere belief with righteous actions will enter Paradise—gardens of eternal beauty with rivers flowing beneath them.",
    "where they will be adorned with bracelets of gold and pearls": "The inhabitants of Paradise will be decorated with jewelry of gold and pearls—symbols of honor, beauty, and the endless blessings Allah has prepared for His faithful servants.",
    "and their clothing will be silk": "Their garments will be of pure silk—the finest and most luxurious fabric. While the disbelievers wear garments of fire, the believers wear garments of silk. The contrast could not be more stark."
  },
  24: {
    "for they have been guided to the best of speech": "The believers earned this reward because in the worldly life, they were guided to the best speech—the declaration of faith (La ilaha illa Allah), the Quran, words of remembrance, and all good and truthful speech. Their tongues were used for what pleases Allah.",
    "and they have been guided to the Commendable Path": "They followed the straight path—the path that leads to Allah, the One worthy of all praise. This path is Islam, the religion that Allah has praised and chosen for humanity. Because they followed this path in the worldly life, they earned eternal reward in the Hereafter."
  },
  52: {
    "Whenever We sent a messenger or a prophet before you ˹O Prophet˺ and he recited ˹Our revelations˺": "Allah consoles the Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) by explaining that every messenger and prophet before him faced challenges when conveying divine revelation. When they recited Allah's words to their people, obstacles arose. This is a pattern throughout prophetic history, not something unique to Muhammad (peace be upon him).",
    "Satan would influence ˹people's understanding of˺ his recitation": "Satan would attempt to interfere with the message—not by corrupting the actual revelation, but by influencing how people understood, received, or interpreted it. Satan works through whispers, doubts, and confusion to distort the truth in people's minds. He might cause people to misunderstand, misquote, or reject what was being recited.",
    "But ˹eventually˺ Allah would eliminate Satan's influence": "However, Allah's power overcomes Satan's schemes. Whatever confusion or distortion Satan tries to introduce, Allah removes and nullifies it. The truth ultimately prevails because Allah protects His message and exposes falsehood.",
    "Then Allah would ˹firmly˺ establish His revelations": "After removing Satan's interference, Allah firmly establishes His verses, making them clear, strong, and unshakeable. The authentic revelation remains preserved and distinguished from any corruption.",
    "And Allah is All-Knowing, All-Wise": "Allah knows exactly what Satan attempts and how to counter it. His wisdom ensures that the divine plan proceeds perfectly, using even Satan's schemes to serve a greater purpose—testing hearts and strengthening the truth."
  },
  53: {
    "All that so He may make Satan's influence a trial for those ˹hypocrites˺ whose hearts are sick": "Allah allows Satan's interference for a purpose: it serves as a test that exposes those with diseased hearts. The hypocrites—whose faith is insincere and whose hearts contain doubt, envy, or hidden disbelief—will be swayed by Satan's whispers and fall into confusion.",
    "and those ˹disbelievers˺ whose hearts are hardened": "Similarly, those whose hearts have become hard through persistent rejection of truth will use Satan's influence as an excuse to further deny the message. Their hearts are like stone—nothing penetrates them.",
    "Surely the wrongdoers are totally engrossed in opposition": "The wrongdoers are deeply entrenched in their opposition to the truth. They are far from guidance, committed to fighting against Allah's message rather than accepting it. Their distance from truth is not accidental—it is a consequence of their choices."
  },
  54: {
    "˹This is˺ also so that those gifted with knowledge would know that this ˹revelation˺ is the truth from your Lord": "Allah's process of establishing truth also serves to confirm faith for the knowledgeable. When they see how Allah nullifies falsehood and establishes truth, their certainty increases. They recognize that the Quran is genuinely from Allah.",
    "so they have faith in it": "This recognition leads to stronger faith. True knowledge produces conviction, and conviction produces submission to the truth.",
    "and so their hearts would submit humbly to it": "Beyond intellectual belief, their hearts become soft and humble before Allah's revelation. They accept it with tranquility and peace, without arrogance or resistance.",
    "And Allah surely guides the believers to the Straight Path": "Allah guarantees guidance to those who believe. He does not abandon sincere believers but continuously leads them toward the straight path, protecting them from Satan's schemes and confirming them in truth."
  },
  55: {
    "Yet the disbelievers will persist in doubt about this ˹revelation˺": "In contrast to the believers who gain certainty, the disbelievers will remain in perpetual doubt. No amount of evidence or miracles will satisfy them because their hearts are sealed. They will continue questioning and denying.",
    "until the Hour takes them by surprise": "Their doubt will only end when death or the Day of Judgment arrives suddenly, catching them unprepared. At that point, the truth will become undeniable, but it will be too late to benefit from belief.",
    "or the torment of a terminating Day comes to them": "The 'terminating Day' refers to a day that ends all their worldly chances—either death or a day of complete destruction from which there is no tomorrow, no offspring, and no continuation. This could refer to the Day of Judgment itself or a day of worldly destruction like what befell previous nations."
  },
  56: {
    "All authority on that Day is for Allah ˹alone˺": "On the Day of Judgment, all forms of power, sovereignty, and authority belong exclusively to Allah. No king, president, or ruler will have any influence. No wealth or status will help. Every apparent authority in this world will be stripped away, and only Allah's dominion will remain.",
    "He will judge between them": "Allah Himself will judge between all creation—believers and disbelievers, oppressors and oppressed, every nation and individual. His judgment will be perfect, fair, and final with no possibility of appeal.",
    "So those who believe and do good will be in the Gardens of Bliss": "The outcome for believers who backed their faith with righteous actions is Paradise—gardens filled with every imaginable blessing and joy. Their faith and deeds earn them eternal happiness."
  },
  57: {
    "But those who disbelieve and deny Our revelations": "Those who rejected faith and specifically denied Allah's signs and revelations—despite having them presented clearly—fall into a different category.",
    "it is they who will suffer a humiliating punishment": "Their punishment will not only be painful but also humiliating. In this life, they may have felt proud and superior in their rejection of truth. In the Hereafter, they will be disgraced and degraded, experiencing the exact opposite of the honor they imagined."
  },
  58: {
    "As for those who emigrate in the cause of Allah": "This refers to believers who leave their homes, families, and possessions to preserve their faith or to serve Allah's cause. The early Muslims who migrated from Makkah to Madinah, leaving everything behind, are primary examples of this.",
    "and then are martyred or die": "Whether these emigrants are killed fighting for Allah's cause (martyrdom) or die of natural causes while in that state of emigration and sacrifice, their reward is the same. The key is their sincere intention and sacrifice for Allah.",
    "Allah will indeed grant them a good provision": "Allah promises to provide for them—not just any provision, but a 'good' or 'beautiful' provision. This refers to the rewards of Paradise, which are pure, eternal, and far beyond anything imaginable in this world.",
    "Surely Allah is the Best Provider": "No one provides like Allah. While humans may provide limited, temporary sustenance, Allah's provision is perfect, complete, and everlasting. Those who sacrifice for Him receive the best from the Best Provider."
  },
  59: {
    "He will certainly admit them into a place they will be pleased with": "Allah emphasizes that He will enter them into an abode that will make them completely satisfied and content. This is Paradise, where every desire is fulfilled and no dissatisfaction exists. The emphasis is on their pleasure—Allah will ensure they are happy with their eternal home.",
    "For Allah is truly All-Knowing, Most Forbearing": "Allah knows exactly what will please each person and prepares it for them. He is also Forbearing—patient with His servants' shortcomings, not rushing to punish, and generously rewarding those who strive for His sake despite their imperfections."
  },
  60: {
    "That is so. And whoever retaliates in equivalence to the injury they have received": "Allah establishes a principle of justice: if someone has been wronged and they retaliate in a manner exactly equal to the wrong done to them—not exceeding it—this is permissible and just. Islam allows proportionate self-defense and retaliation.",
    "and then are wronged ˹again˺": "If after this justified retaliation, the person is wronged yet again by the aggressor or others, they have a special promise from Allah.",
    "Allah will certainly help them": "Allah guarantees His assistance to those who act justly but continue to face aggression. He will support and aid them against their oppressors. This is a promise to the oppressed that they are not alone.",
    "Surely Allah is Ever-Pardoning, All-Forgiving": "Despite discussing retaliation, Allah reminds us of His nature: He pardons and forgives. This subtly encourages believers to also pardon when possible, even though retaliation is permitted. Forgiveness is a higher path, reflecting Allah's own attributes."
  },
  61: {
    "That is because Allah causes the night to merge into the day, and the day into the night": "Allah's power to help the oppressed and establish justice is demonstrated by His control over creation. He seamlessly causes night and day to transition into each other—lengthening and shortening them according to seasons, merging darkness into light and light into darkness. This daily phenomenon that we take for granted is evidence of His absolute control.",
    "Indeed, Allah is All-Hearing, All-Seeing": "Allah hears everything—the prayers of the oppressed, the plots of the wrongdoers, every word spoken in public or secret. He sees everything—the actions of the just and unjust, what is done openly and what is hidden. Nothing escapes His awareness."
  },
  62: {
    "That is because Allah ˹alone˺ is the Truth": "All of Allah's power and authority stem from the fact that He alone is the ultimate Truth and Reality. Everything else is dependent on Him, but He depends on nothing. His existence is necessary; everything else is contingent.",
    "and what they invoke besides Him is falsehood": "In contrast, anything worshipped besides Allah—idols, saints, spirits, or any other beings—is falsehood with no reality or power. They cannot create, sustain, harm, or benefit. They are false gods built on human imagination.",
    "and Allah ˹alone˺ is truly the Most High, All-Great": "Allah is exalted above all creation, above all deficiency, above all partners. He is the Greatest—nothing compares to Him in power, knowledge, or majesty. This concludes the logical argument: since Allah alone is True, Great, and High, He alone deserves worship."
  },
  63: {
    "Do you not see that Allah sends down rain from the sky, then the earth becomes green?": "Allah draws attention to a common but profound miracle: He sends rain from above, and dry, barren earth transforms into lush green landscapes. This cycle of death and revival in nature points to Allah's power to resurrect humans after death.",
    "Surely Allah is Most Subtle, All-Aware": "Allah's actions are subtle—He works in ways beyond our complete understanding. The process of rain forming, falling, and reviving the earth involves countless intricate steps that we often overlook. He is also All-Aware—knowing every detail of His creation and every need of His creatures."
  },
  64: {
    "To Him belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is on the earth": "Allah owns everything—every star, planet, angel, human, animal, plant, and atom. Nothing exists outside His ownership. This universal ownership means He has complete authority over all things.",
    "Allah ˹alone˺ is truly the Self-Sufficient, Praiseworthy": "Allah needs nothing from His creation. He is not dependent on worship, provision, or assistance from anyone. He is Self-Sufficient. Yet despite needing nothing, He is worthy of all praise—Praiseworthy in His essence, His actions, and His attributes."
  },
  65: {
    "Do you not see that Allah has subjected to you whatever is in the earth": "Allah calls attention to His enormous favor upon humanity: He has made everything on earth subservient to human benefit. Animals can be ridden and eaten, plants provide food and medicine, minerals serve countless purposes—all by Allah's design for human service.",
    "as well as the ships ˹that˺ sail through the sea by His command": "Ships—massive vessels carrying people and cargo across vast oceans—float and sail by Allah's command. He created water with properties that allow ships to float, wind that propels sails, and materials that humans fashion into vessels. All of this serves humanity.",
    "He keeps the sky from falling down on the earth except by His permission": "The celestial bodies—stars, moons, and all heavenly objects—remain in their places by Allah's will. If He permitted, they could crash down upon the earth. The stability of the cosmos is maintained by His command alone.",
    "Surely Allah is Ever Gracious and Most Merciful to humanity": "All of these blessings demonstrate Allah's immense grace and mercy toward humans. Despite human ingratitude and disobedience, Allah continues to provide, protect, and sustain. His mercy encompasses everything."
  },
  66: {
    "And He is the One Who gave you life": "Allah alone brought us into existence from nothing. We had no existence, no consciousness, no being—then Allah gave us life. This first creation is a miracle we often forget.",
    "then will cause you to die": "After the appointed time of life, Allah will cause each person to die. Death is certain and decreed by Allah for every living soul. It is part of His plan.",
    "and then will bring you back to life": "After death, Allah will resurrect everyone for judgment. The same power that created life the first time will restore it. This is the central truth that the Quran repeatedly emphasizes.",
    "˹But˺ surely humankind is ever ungrateful": "Despite all these blessings—life, provision, protection, and the promise of eternal reward—humans are characteristically ungrateful. We forget Allah's favors, complain about what we lack, and fail to worship Him properly. This is a sobering reminder of a human weakness we must struggle against."
  },
  67: {
    "For every community We appointed a code of life to follow": "Allah explains that different religious communities throughout history were given different ritual practices and laws suited to their time and circumstances. The Jews had their law, the Christians theirs, and now the Muslims have been given the final, complete code. The core message of monotheism was always the same, but specific practices varied.",
    "So do not let them dispute with you ˹O Prophet˺ in this matter": "When people from other religions argue about religious practices—claiming their way is the only correct way or that Islam's practices are new or wrong—the Prophet should not be drawn into fruitless disputes. Each community was given what was appropriate for them.",
    "And invite ˹all˺ to your Lord, for you are truly on the Right Guidance": "Instead of debating, the Prophet should focus on inviting all people to worship Allah alone. His message is the final and complete guidance—the Right Guidance that corrects any deviations from previous communities."
  },
  68: {
    "But if they argue with you, then say, \"Allah knows best what you do.\"": "If people persist in arguing despite the clear invitation to truth, the Prophet should respond by reminding them that Allah is fully aware of everyone's actions. This is both a warning—that they will be held accountable for their choices—and a way to end unproductive debates by referring the matter to the All-Knowing Judge."
  },
  69: {
    "Allah will judge between you ˹all˺ on Judgment Day regarding your differences": "All religious disputes—who was right, whose practices were accepted, whose beliefs were true—will be settled by Allah Himself on the Day of Judgment. No human arbitration is needed. The final verdict belongs to Allah, and on that Day, all truth will become clear."
  },
  70: {
    "Do you not know that Allah ˹fully˺ knows whatever is in the heavens and the earth?": "Allah's knowledge is complete and comprehensive. He knows everything in the heavens and the earth—every thought, intention, action, and event. Nothing is hidden from Him.",
    "Surely it is all ˹written˺ in a Record": "Everything that exists and everything that happens is recorded in the Preserved Tablet (Al-Lawh Al-Mahfuz). This divine record contains all knowledge, and nothing occurs except what is written in it.",
    "That is certainly easy for Allah": "While recording and knowing everything might seem impossible to humans, it is effortless for Allah. His capabilities are unlimited, and what seems miraculous to us is simple for Him."
  },
  71: {
    "Yet they worship besides Allah that for which He has sent down no authority": "People worship deities, idols, and beings for which Allah has provided no justification or evidence. No prophet was sent to authorize such worship, no scripture commands it, and no logical argument supports it. It is worship without divine sanction.",
    "and of which they have no knowledge": "These worshippers have no real knowledge about their objects of worship—they cannot prove these false gods have any power, any awareness, or any ability to help or harm. Their worship is based on ignorance, inherited customs, or baseless assumptions.",
    "The wrongdoers will have no helper": "Those who commit this grave wrong of worshipping other than Allah will find no one to help them on the Day of Judgment. Their false gods will abandon them, and they will face consequences alone."
  },
  72: {
    "Whenever Our clear revelations are recited to them, you ˹O Prophet˺ recognize rage on the faces of the disbelievers": "When the Quran's clear verses are read to the disbelievers, their faces twist with anger and hatred. The truth disturbs them so deeply that their internal rage becomes visible on their faces. They cannot hide their hostility toward Allah's words.",
    "as if they are going to snap at those who recite Our revelations to them": "Their anger is so intense that they seem ready to physically attack the reciters. They want to silence the truth by any means because they cannot refute it intellectually.",
    "Say, \"Shall I inform you of something far more enraging than that?": "The Prophet is instructed to respond to their rage by asking: shall I tell you about something that should really make you furious—something far worse than hearing these verses?",
    "˹It is˺ the Fire with which Allah has threatened those who disbelieve": "What should truly anger and concern them is the Hellfire that awaits disbelievers. Their rage at hearing the Quran is misplaced—they should instead fear the punishment that Allah has promised for those who reject His message.",
    "What an evil destination!": "The Hellfire is described as the worst possible destination. This rhetorical exclamation emphasizes the horror of where disbelief leads."
  },
  73: {
    "O humanity! A lesson is set forth, so listen to it ˹carefully˺": "Allah calls all of humanity to pay close attention to an important example that exposes the absurdity of idol worship. This is not a trivial point—it is a fundamental lesson that everyone must understand.",
    "those ˹idols˺ you invoke besides Allah can never create ˹so much as˺ a fly, even if they ˹all˺ were to come together for that": "All the false gods that people worship—combined together—cannot create even a single fly. The fly is among the smallest, most insignificant creatures, yet these so-called deities cannot produce one. If they lack the power to create a fly, how can they be gods worthy of worship?",
    "And if a fly were to snatch anything away from them, they cannot ˹even˺ retrieve it from the fly": "Even more humiliating: if a fly lands on the offerings placed before idols and takes something away, the idols cannot recover it. They are utterly powerless—not only unable to create but unable to protect what is given to them from an insect.",
    "How powerless are those who invoke and those invoked!": "Both parties are weak and pathetic: the worshippers who call upon helpless idols, and the idols that cannot respond. The worship is futile, the gods are fake, and the entire system is exposed as baseless. This powerful example should convince any rational person to abandon idol worship."
  },
  74: {
    "They have not shown Allah the reverence He deserves": "Those who worship idols alongside Allah have failed to appreciate Allah's true greatness. They have not estimated Him correctly. To place created beings—which cannot even create a fly—alongside the Creator of everything is a profound insult to Allah's majesty.",
    "Surely Allah is All-Powerful, Almighty": "In contrast to powerless idols, Allah possesses all power and might. He is Strong—nothing can overcome Him. He is Almighty—He dominates all things and is never dominated. This is the God who deserves worship, not helpless idols."
  },
  75: {
    "Allah selects messengers from both angels and people": "Allah chooses messengers from among the angels—like Jibreel (Gabriel) who delivers revelation—and from among humans—like all the prophets from Adam to Muhammad (peace be upon them all). This selection is Allah's exclusive right; He knows who is best suited for these noble tasks.",
    "for Allah is truly All-Hearing, All-Seeing": "Allah's selection is based on perfect knowledge. He hears everything and sees everything, so He knows exactly who deserves to be chosen for these sacred missions. His choices are never arbitrary but based on complete awareness."
  },
  76: {
    "He knows what is ahead of them and what is behind them": "Allah's knowledge encompasses all of time—what has already happened and what will happen in the future. Nothing in past, present, or future is hidden from Him. He knows the complete reality of everything.",
    "And to Allah ˹all˺ matters will be returned ˹for judgment˺": "Every matter, every affair, every action will ultimately return to Allah for final decision and judgment. No issue remains unresolved forever—Allah will settle everything with perfect justice."
  },
  77: {
    "O believers! Bow down, prostrate yourselves": "Allah directly addresses those who believe, commanding them to perform the physical acts of worship: bowing (ruku') and prostrating (sujud). These are the core physical components of prayer, representing submission and humility before Allah.",
    "worship your Lord": "Beyond the physical acts, believers are commanded to worship Allah in the complete sense—with their hearts, tongues, and limbs. Worship encompasses all acts of obedience and devotion to Allah alone.",
    "and do ˹what is˺ good so that you may be successful": "Along with ritual worship, believers must do good deeds—acts of kindness, charity, justice, and righteousness in all areas of life. This combination of worship and good conduct leads to ultimate success in this world and the Hereafter."
  },
  78: {
    "Strive for ˹the cause of˺ Allah in the way He deserves": "Believers are commanded to exert themselves completely for Allah's cause. This striving (jihad) includes struggling against one's own desires, against Satan's whispers, against injustice, and—when necessary—physical defense of the faith. The striving should be sincere and complete, as Allah deserves.",
    "for ˹it is˺ He ˹Who˺ has chosen you": "This is a great honor—Allah has selected this Ummah (nation) for the final message. Being chosen comes with responsibility, but it is also a tremendous blessing that should inspire gratitude and dedication.",
    "and laid upon you no hardship in the religion": "Allah has not burdened believers with an impossible religion. Islam is practical and manageable. When genuine hardship exists, Islam provides flexibility and ease. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said, 'Religion is ease.' This should encourage believers—the path to success is not unbearably difficult.",
    "the way of your forefather Abraham": "The religion given to Muslims is the same pure monotheism of Ibrahim (Abraham), the patriarch beloved by all. Muslims are not following something new—they are reviving the original, uncorrupted faith of Ibrahim.",
    "˹It is Allah˺ Who named you 'the ones who submit' ˹in the˺ earlier ˹Scriptures˺ and in this ˹Quran˺": "Allah Himself named this nation 'Muslims' (those who submit) in previous scriptures and in the Quran. This name defines the community's identity: complete submission to Allah's will.",
    "so that the Messenger may be a witness over you, and that you may be witnesses over humanity": "The Prophet (peace be upon him) will testify about this Ummah on the Day of Judgment—that he delivered the message to them. In turn, this Ummah will be witnesses over all of humanity—testifying that prophets were sent to every nation. This is a weighty responsibility.",
    "So establish prayer, pay alms-tax": "The surah concludes with two practical commands: establish regular prayer (the connection with Allah) and pay Zakat (the connection with society). These two pillars support all of Islamic practice.",
    "and hold fast to Allah": "Hold firmly to Allah—trust in Him, rely on Him, seek help from Him, and never let go of your connection to Him. He is the strongest support.",
    "He ˹alone˺ is your Guardian": "Allah is the protector, supporter, and caretaker of the believers. No one else can fulfill this role as He can.",
    "What an excellent Guardian, and what an excellent Helper!": "The surah ends with praise for Allah—He is the best possible protector and the best possible helper. Believers who hold fast to Him have secured the greatest ally and support in existence. This is encouragement and comfort for all who follow the path of Islam."
  },
  101: {
    "Surely those for whom We have destined the finest reward": "After describing the horrors of Hell, Allah now contrasts it with the fate of the righteous. Those for whom Allah has decreed 'al-husna' (the finest reward, Paradise) will have a completely different experience. This includes the prophets, the martyrs, the truthful, and all sincere believers. Allah's prior decree of good for them is based on His knowledge of their faith and righteous deeds.",
    "will be kept far away from Hell": "These blessed individuals will be removed far from Hell—not just saved from entering it, but kept at a distance from it entirely. They will not see it, smell it, or experience any of its horrors. This distancing is itself a mercy and a reward."
  },
  102: {
    "not even hearing the slightest hissing from it": "The people of Paradise will not hear even the faintest sound of Hell—not its roaring, crackling, or the cries of its inhabitants. Their tranquility will be complete and undisturbed. This contrasts with the previous verse about the people of Hell who cannot hear anything pleasant; the people of Paradise will not hear anything distressing.",
    "And they will delight forever in what their souls desire": "In Paradise, every desire will be fulfilled. Whatever their hearts wish for—whether food, drink, companionship, scenery, or pleasures we cannot imagine—will be provided. And this bliss is eternal (khalidoon)—it never ends, never diminishes, and never becomes boring. The pleasures of this world always fade, but the pleasures of Paradise are forever fresh and satisfying."
  },
  103: {
    "The Supreme Horror ˹of that Day˺ will not disturb them": "The Day of Judgment will feature terrifying events—the earth shaking, the mountains crumbling, the sun darkened, and people fleeing in panic. This is called 'al-faza' al-akbar' (the Supreme Horror). But the righteous will be protected from this terror. While others panic, they will be at peace, secure in Allah's protection. Some narrations indicate that the believers will be shaded and comforted while others suffer the terrors of that Day.",
    "and the angels will greet them, ˹saying,˺ \"This is your Day, which you have been promised\"": "Instead of facing horror, the righteous will be welcomed by angels with congratulations. The angels will announce that this is the Day they were promised—the Day of reward for their patience and faith. Imagine the joy of hearing this greeting after years of striving, sacrifice, and worship. All the hardships of worldly life become worthwhile in this moment of angelic welcome."
  },
  104: {
    "On that Day We will roll up the heavens like a scroll of writings": "Allah describes the immense power He will display on the Day of Judgment. The vast heavens—with all their stars, galaxies, and cosmic structures—will be rolled up as easily as one rolls up a piece of paper. This imagery conveys both the ease with which Allah handles creation and the total transformation that will occur. Nothing of the current universe will remain as it was.",
    "Just as We produced the first creation, ˹so˺ shall We reproduce it": "Allah presents a logical argument for resurrection: if He created everything from nothing the first time, recreating it is even easier. The One who originated life has full power to restore it. Those who doubt resurrection should consider their own existence—they were nothing, then Allah brought them into being. Restoring them after death is simpler than the original creation.",
    "That is a promise binding on Us": "Allah has promised resurrection and judgment, and His promise is absolutely binding. Unlike humans who may break promises due to inability or dishonesty, Allah always fulfills His word. This is not just a possibility but a certainty—a divine commitment.",
    "We truly uphold ˹Our promises˺!": "Allah emphasizes His track record of fulfilling promises. Every promise made to previous nations was kept—rewards for the righteous, punishment for the wicked, support for the prophets. The promise of the Day of Judgment will be fulfilled just as certainly."
  },
  105: {
    "Surely, following the ˹heavenly˺ Record, We decreed in the Scriptures": "After the 'Dhikr' (which some scholars say refers to the Preserved Tablet or the Torah), Allah decreed in the 'Zabur' (Psalms given to David) a consistent message. This shows continuity between revelations—the same truths were revealed across scriptures.",
    "\"My righteous servants shall inherit the land\"": "This decree promises that ultimately, the righteous will prevail and inherit the earth. This can refer to inheriting Paradise (called 'the land' or 'the earth' of the Hereafter), or to the eventual victory of truth over falsehood in this world, or both. The promise found in Psalm 37:29 similarly states that the righteous will inherit the land. This cross-scriptural confirmation shows the unity of Allah's message and gives believers hope that despite temporary setbacks, ultimate victory belongs to the faithful."
  },
  106: {
    "Surely this ˹Quran˺ is sufficient ˹as a reminder˺ for those devoted to worship": "Allah declares that the Quran contains everything needed for guidance. For those who are devoted to worshipping Allah (qawm 'abideen), the Quran provides complete direction. They do not need additional miracles or signs—the Quran itself is sufficient. This verse identifies the target audience of the Quran's message: those who sincerely seek to worship Allah will find it fully satisfying. Those who reject it do so not because the Quran is deficient but because they lack sincerity."
  },
  107: {
    "We have sent you ˹O Prophet˺ only as a mercy for the whole world": "This is one of the most important verses describing the Prophet Muhammad's mission. He was sent as 'rahmatan lil-'alameen'—a mercy to all the worlds. Not just to Arabs, not just to Muslims, but to all of humanity, jinn, and creation. His teachings bring mercy by guiding people away from Hell to Paradise, from ignorance to knowledge, from injustice to justice, from chaos to peace. Even non-Muslims benefit from the justice, ethics, and civilizational values Islam brought. The Prophet himself said, 'I was not sent to curse people but as a mercy.' His entire life exemplified compassion, forgiveness, and concern for others' welfare."
  },
  108: {
    "Say, \"What has been revealed to me is this: 'Your God is only One God.'": "The Prophet is commanded to summarize his core message: there is only One God worthy of worship. This is the essence of all prophetic teaching from Adam to Muhammad. Despite the Quran's many topics—law, history, ethics, afterlife—this central message of monotheism (tawheed) is the foundation of everything else.",
    "Will you then submit?\"": "After stating the truth clearly, the Prophet asks them to respond: will you submit to this truth and become Muslims (those who submit to Allah)? The choice is theirs. The evidence has been presented, the message is clear, and now the decision rests with each individual. 'Islam' literally means submission, and the question asks whether they will submit to the One True God."
  },
  109: {
    "If they turn away, then say, \"I have warned you all equally": "If they reject the message, the Prophet has fulfilled his duty. He has warned everyone equally and fairly—no one can claim they were not informed. The Prophet's responsibility was to convey the message clearly (balagh), not to force acceptance. He has done his part; they are responsible for their choice.",
    "I do not know if what you are threatened with is near or far": "The Prophet honestly admits he does not know the exact timing of the punishment or the Day of Judgment. This knowledge belongs only to Allah. The threat is real and certain, but its timing is unknown. This honest admission enhances the Prophet's credibility—he only claims knowledge of what has been revealed to him."
  },
  110: {
    "Allah surely knows what you say openly": "Allah is fully aware of every public statement—the mockery, the accusations, the rejection spoken aloud. Nothing escapes His hearing.",
    "and whatever you hide": "More significantly, Allah also knows what they conceal in their hearts—their secret doubts, their private recognition of truth, their hidden plots against the Prophet. Some may have known the truth but hid it out of pride or worldly interests. Allah knows everything, and all will be accounted for."
  },
  111: {
    "I do not know if this ˹delay˺ is possibly a test for you": "The Prophet acknowledges another possibility: perhaps the delay in punishment is itself a test. Allah may be giving them time to see if they will repent or if they will become more arrogant in their disbelief. Time is not always a blessing—it can be a test that exposes one's true character.",
    "and an enjoyment for a while": "Or perhaps the delay allows them to enjoy worldly life for a limited period before facing consequences. This enjoyment is temporary (ila heen—until a fixed time), and when it ends, accountability begins. The delay should not be mistaken for approval or escape from consequences."
  },
  112: {
    "˹In the end,˺ the Prophet said, \"My Lord! Judge ˹between us˺ in truth": "The Prophet turns to Allah, asking Him to judge between the believers and disbelievers with truth and justice. This is not a request for premature punishment but an appeal to the ultimate Judge. The Prophet leaves the matter to Allah, trusting in His perfect justice. This teaches believers to ultimately rely on Allah's judgment rather than taking matters into their own hands.",
    "And our Lord is the Most Compassionate": "Even while asking for judgment, the Prophet invokes Allah's mercy (Ar-Rahman). This balance between justice and mercy is characteristic of Islamic teaching. Allah is just but also infinitely merciful. The believers hope for His mercy while the wrongdoers should fear His justice.",
    "Whose help is sought against what you claim": "The Prophet seeks Allah's help against the false claims the disbelievers make—their accusations that the Quran is fabricated, that Muhammad is a poet or madman, that their idols have power. Allah's help is sufficient against all falsehood. This final statement of the surah is a prayer and a declaration of reliance on Allah. No matter what the enemies say or do, the believers have Allah on their side, and that is enough."
  }
};